  "query": "How does the success of providing artificial nest sites for solitary bees compare to providing them for bumblebees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across multiple trials, artificial nest sites are more consistently used by solitary bees than by bumblebees. For solitary bees, 29 of 30 replicated trials reported occupancy, with reported occupancy of 1\u201326% of available cavities, many species using boxes, and some studies recording increased local populations or occupied nests doubling over three years with repeated provision [47],[80]. By contrast, bumblebee nest boxes show low and variable uptake: two replicated trials reported \u22642% occupancy, three UK trials since 1989 found 0\u20132.5% for several designs, while earlier and some North American studies reported 10\u201348% overall; underground designs perform better with 6\u201358% occupancy, but there is no captured evidence that nest boxes increase bumblebee populations [80],[48].",
  "action_ids": [
