  "query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the success of captive rearing and subsequent reintroduction of bumblebees into the wild?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence on captive rearing includes 22 trials from 13 countries using varied methods (queens alone, with workers, honey bee workers, male pupae, or CO2 anaesthesia), with one trial observing a gradual decrease in Bombus terrestris queen weight over four years [50]. Trials on North American declining species show mixed captive-rearing outcomes: B. vagans queens reared adults; B. terricola and B. rufocinctus queens reared adults in some attempts; B. fervidus queens laid eggs but larvae died before adulthood across three trials; similar larval mortality was reported for B. affinis (rusty-patched) and B. pensylvanicus; B. ruderatus was also successfully reared; and laboratory rearing was reported for the pocket-making B. atratus [50]. Captive-rearing performance is influenced by diet and husbandry: freshly frozen pollen increased queen size and subsequent colony performance versus dried frozen pollen, higher-protein pollen increased worker offspring production, an 8L:16D light regime shortened time to egg-laying, and specific hibernation regimes affected survival and colony formation (e.g., 4\u20135\u00b0C for 45 days enhanced egg-laying/colony formation but yielded smaller colonies; survival likelihood improved for queens >0.6 g and hibernated \u22644 months) [50]. For reintroduction of laboratory-reared colonies, seven replicated field trials report mixed success: in four trials (three UK, one Canada) colonies were monitored until new queens emerged or the founding queen died; two UK trials yielded very low or zero new queens per colony, whereas two other trials produced good numbers of new queens [52]. Social parasitism rates after release were variable: two replicated trials (Canada, UK) found high parasitism (25\u201366% and 79% respectively), and parasitism was reduced by placing colonies in landscapes with intermediate rather than very high floral resources and by releasing later in the season; five other trials reported no social parasites [52]. Supplementary feeding produced inconsistent benefits: one Canadian trial improved reproductive success without reducing parasite load, while a USA trial found no increase in productivity; a small Norwegian trial found released B. terrestris foraged mostly >100 m from nests [52].",
