  "query": "How do the impacts of planting floral resources for bees differ when implemented at a local patch scale versus a wider landscape scale?",
  "relevant_summary": "At the local patch scale, multiple trials report that sown flower patches on farmland attract substantial numbers of foraging wild bees, especially bumblebees, with observed species counts ranging from 8 to 35 on phacelia-rich patches, although attractiveness can vary by region (e.g., lower in Greece) [17]. Patch-scale interventions have shown mixed evidence for broader population responses: one trial found planted lupine patches in apple orchards significantly enhanced the reproductive success of Osmia lignaria, while another found bee numbers and species richness in farmland 50\u20131,500 m away from planted patches were not higher; two trials reported no or relatively few solitary bees nesting on set-aside fields sown with phacelia or clover [17]. Field margins sown with agricultural nectar and pollen mixes, particularly perennial leguminous plants, attract significantly more foraging bumblebees than naturally regenerated, grassy, or cropped margins, though their value may degrade over time and require re-sowing every few years [18]. At the wider landscape scale, one large replicated controlled trial found that the average abundance of long-tongued bumblebees on field margins was positively correlated with the number of \u2018pollen and nectar\u2019 agri-environment agreements within a 10 km grid square [21, 362]. Additionally, the attractiveness of planted perennial leguminous herbs to bumblebees increased in landscapes with a greater proportion of arable farming, indicating landscape context can influence patch-level outcomes [17].",
